AN ACT relating to juvenile justice; revising provisions limiting the period during
which a juvenile court may place a child on probation; authorizing the
juvenile court to terminate the probation of a child who has failed to
make full restitution under certain circumstances; prescribing the
procedure to be used by the juvenile court in determining whether to
suspend, modify or revoke the probation of a child; and providing
other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law authorizes a juvenile court to place a child on probation under certain
2 circumstances. With certain exceptions, existing law prohibits a juvenile court from placing a
3 child on probation for a period of more than 18 months for each unlawful act for which the
4 child is adjudicated delinquent, placed under the supervision of the juvenile court or placed
5 under informal supervision. (NRS 62E.708) Section 1 of this bill removes language that ties
6 the period during which a juvenile court may place a child on probation to each unlawful act
7 for which the child is adjudicated delinquent . [, placed under the supervision of the juvenile
8 court or placed under informal supervision.] Section 1 thereby prohibits a juvenile court from
9 placing a child on probation for a period of more than 18 months, regardless of the number of
10 unlawful acts for which the child is adjudicated delinquent, [placed under the supervision of
11 the juvenile court or placed under informal supervision,] unless an exception applies.
12 Existing law authorizes the juvenile court to enter a civil judgment against a child or a
13 parent or guardian of a child for any amount of restitution that remains unpaid after the time
14 established by the juvenile court for its payment. (NRS 62B.420) Under existing law, the
15 juvenile court retains jurisdiction over a child, parent or guardian against whom a civil
16 judgment is entered, regardless of whether the period of probation of the child has been
17 terminated. (NRS 62B.420, 62E.708) Section 1 authorizes the juvenile court to terminate the
18 period of probation of a child who has failed to make full restitution but has otherwise
19 fulfilled the conditions of his or her probation. If the juvenile court terminates the period of
20 probation of a child who has failed to make full restitution pursuant to section 1, existing law
21 authorizes the juvenile court to enter a civil judgment against the child or the parent or
22 guardian of the child for the amount due in favor of the victim. (NRS 62B.420)
23 Existing law prescribes the procedure to be used by the juvenile court in determining
24 whether to suspend, modify or revoke the parole of a child who violates the terms and

