25 conditions of his or her parole. Under existing law, pursuant to this procedure, the juvenile
26 court must: (1) hold a hearing to determine whether to suspend, modify or revoke the parole
27 of the child; (2) render a decision within 10 days after the conclusion of the hearing; and (3)
28 comply with certain other requirements. (NRS 63.770) Existing law authorizes the juvenile
29 court to order a child who violates the terms of his or her probation to be placed in a facility
30 for the detention of children or county jail for not more than 30 days for the violation. (NRS
31 62E.710) Section 2 of this bill establishes the procedure to be used by the juvenile court when
32 a child violates the conditions of his or her probation which is similar to the procedure
33 established for violations of parole. Section 2 thereby requires the juvenile court to hold a
34 hearing before ordering a child who violates the conditions of his or her probation to be placed
35 in a facility for the detention of children or county jail.
